2. High-Level Architecture
Overview

The HBnB system follows a layered architecture to separate responsibilities and improve maintainability. Each layer focuses on a specific role within the application.

The architecture consists of three primary layers:

Presentation Layer
Business Logic Layer
Persistence Layer

Presentation Layer

The Presentation Layer handles client interactions through API endpoints. It receives requests from clients and forwards them to the appropriate services.

Responsibilities include:

Handling HTTP requests
Validating input data
Returning API responses

Business Logic Layer

The Business Logic Layer contains the core models and services responsible for implementing the application's rules and behaviors.

Responsibilities include:

Managing domain entities
Processing business operations
Coordinating interactions between objects

Persistence Layer

The Persistence Layer is responsible for database access and data storage.

Responsibilities include:

Saving and retrieving data
Managing database queries
Providing repository interfaces for the business layer

