last_name
email
password
places
reviews

Place
Represents a property listed by a user.

Attributes include:

title
description
price
owner
address
max_guests
reviews

Review
Represents feedback written by users about a place.

Attributes include:

reviewer
place
rating
comment
author

Amenity
Represents features that can be associated with places.

Attributes include:

name
description
created_at
updated_at

Entity Relationships

User → Place
A user can own multiple places.

User → Review
A user can write multiple reviews.

Place → Review
A place can have multiple reviews.

Place → Amenity
A place can have multiple amenities.

4. API Interaction Flow
Sequence Diagram

The following diagram illustrates how the system processes a user registration request.

Flow Explanation

Client
Sends a request to create a new user account.

API Controller
Receives the request and validates the input data.

User Service
Processes the request and creates the user object.

User Model
Instantiates the user entity.

User Repository
Handles saving the user data to the database.

Database
Stores the new user record and returns a success confirmation.

5. Design Notes
Architectural Decisions

Layered Architecture
Separates the system into presentation, logic, and persistence layers to improve modularity.

Object-Oriented Design
Encapsulation and abstraction are used to organize the application into reusable components.

Facade Pattern
The API layer simplifies interactions with the underlying models and services.

Repository Pattern
Repositories handle database interactions, allowing business logic to remain independent from database details.

6. System Integration

The components interact in the following way:

The client sends a request to the API.

The API validates the request and forwards it to the appropriate service.

The service processes the business logic.

The repository stores or retrieves data from the database.

The API returns the response to the client.

